Also screenshotted is the Driver Station and the SysID connection indicator. Any help would be greatly appreciated.

posts.name: Joe Ross
posts.cooked: That’s no longer necessary as the fix has been released in wpilib 2023.2.1

posts.name: mjbergman92
posts.cooked: I just updated to 2023.2.1 and issue has been resolved. You just have to download 1.8gb for another version of WPILib. I wish they had a way of downloading a small update, but the current way works.

posts.name: Lee
posts.cooked: Updating to 2023.2.1 fixed it for me. Thanks!

posts.name: Thad House
posts.cooked: A smaller installer would only save ~300mb. An extremely large majority of what’s in the installer is versioned to each update, and would need to be downloaded anyway.

posts.name: Jainish Patel
posts.cooked: Do I have to download the .iso for 2023.2.1 or just update through command palette? I update through command palette and I’m still facing the issue.

posts.name: Thad House
posts.cooked: The command palette won’t update c++ tools, so you have to use the new installer.

posts.name: Jainish Patel
posts.cooked: It still doesn’t work. After running the first test the NT disconnects and reconnects over and over. Also, for some reason I have two clients.

posts.name: Brendan R.
posts.cooked:
JaiCodes:

Also, for some reason I have two clients.

WPI released NetworkTables 4.0, which completely rewrote NT3.0. I’m guessing both clients are here so you can use the tools with RoboRios that are up-to-date (2023 version with NT4) or RoboRios that are out of date (2022- version with NT3)

You can read about it here: Migrating from NetworkTables 3.0 to NetworkTables 4.0 — FIRST Robotics Competition documentation

Depending on which server version you have, you should choose a different client.

If you have updated your RoboRIO to 2023 version, you should try the NT4 version

link_counts.title: Migrating from NetworkTables 3.0 to NetworkTables 4.0 — FIRST Robotics Competition documentation

posts.name: Jainish Patel
posts.cooked: Thank you! It defaults to NT3 and switching to NT4 before running tests solved the issue!

posts.name: Joel Singh
posts.cooked:
Hello! My robot is not connecting on SysID through network tables. I am able to successfully deploy from SysID but I can’t connect, it says “NT Disconnected”. My SysID version is v2023.3.2 and my rio version according to driver station is 2023_v3.1. I’ve tried connecting through NT4 and NT3. And i’ve tried rebooting the rio. Communications is green on driver station and robot code is red. Does anybody else know anything else I can try?

Edit: nevermind, restarting the laptop fixed it. Edit edit: deploying the code caused NT to become disconnected, I’ve now discovered the issue to be the fact that I had “Encoder port” selected rather than “Data port”.
